<subSubSection id="50C06544C00CFFC2FDDEFB26EDBACC05" lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="190" pageId="26" pageNumber="189" type="description">
<paragraph id="186536CFC00CFFC3FDDEFB26ED4ECA8E" blockId="26.[365,958,1142,1198]" box="[543,780,1174,1198]" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">
(
<figureCitation id="80E12A4AC00CFFC3FDE6FB26EC94CA8E" box="[551,726,1174,1198]" captionStart="Figures 22–43" captionStartId="17.[125,194,1502,1521]" captionTargetBox="[175,1127,218,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-1@17.[170,1127,192,1466]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figures 22–43. Adults of Metallolophia. (22, 23) M. assamensis Orhant (paratype, „, ZSM): (22) upperside, (23) underside. (24, 25) M. arenaria (Leech) (lectotype, ♀, BMNH): (24) upperside, (25) underside. (26, 27) M. arenaria (Leech) („, IZCAS): (26) upperside, (27) underside. (28, 29) M. cuneataria sp. nov. (holotype, „, IZCAS): (28) upperside, (29) underside. (30, 31) M. inanularia sp. nov. (holotype, ♀, IZCAS): (30) upperside, (31) underside. (32, 33) M. ocellata (Warren) (holotype, ♀, BMNH); (32) upperside, (33) underside. (34, 35) M. ocellata (Warren) („, ORHANT); (34) upperside, (35) underside. (36, 37) M. devecisi Herbulot (holotype, „, ZSM): (36) upperside, (37) underside." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5214614" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5214614/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">Figures 30, 31</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="80E12A4AC00CFFC3FD25FB26ED41CA8E" box="[740,771,1174,1198]" captionStart="Figures 75–78" captionStartId="24.[138,207,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[193,1132,141,1269]" captionTargetId="figure-47@24.[183,1140,133,1279]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figures 75–78. Female genitalia. (75) M. arenaria (BMNH Geom-20967). (76) M. cuneataria sp. nov., holotype (IZCAS Geom-00101). (77) M. inanularia sp. nov., holotype (IZCAS Geom-00102). (78) M. deveccisi (ZSM). Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5214628" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5214628/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">77</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00CFFC3FF4BFB57EF41CADF" blockId="26.[138,259,1255,1279]" box="[138,259,1255,1279]" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00CFFC3FF4BFB57EF41CADF" box="[138,259,1255,1279]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00CFFC3FF4BFAA8EC15C8B4" blockId="26.[138,1185,1304,1684]" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00CFFC3FF4BFAA8EEA3CB10" box="[138,225,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">Female.</emphasis>
Length of fore wing: 
<quantity id="DF229B2AC00CFFC3FE22FAA8EC7ECB10" box="[483,572,1304,1328]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="189" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
. Large. Frons black, palpus brown, mixed with grey. Body and wings scattered with extensive olive green. Outer margins of both wings weakly crenulate. Fore wing with transverse lines much thicker than in the two previous species; antemedian line deeply curved convexly, not with a double undulation as in its allies; postmedian line angled on M 
<subScript id="845E348AC00CFFC3FE1CFA14EFAACB94" attach="left" box="[477,488,1444,1460]" fontSize="7" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">3</subScript>
(curved in the previous two species); large olive green discal spot almost without ring. Hind wing with discal spot very weak, the black postmedian line thin and clear. On underside, discal spots large, especially on hind wing, where spot expanded on both sides, proximally touching the patch in the cell and distally extending to the band-like postmedian line, which on both wings placed more proximally than in the allied species; subterminal band dark purple but much reduced, becoming a row of joined spots below M 
<subScript id="845E348AC00CFFC3FEF9F9D6EF01C856" attach="left" box="[312,323,1638,1654]" fontSize="7" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">3</subScript>
on both wings; without light violet suffusion below cell and Cu 
<subScript id="845E348AC00CFFC3FBF9F9D6EA01C856" attach="left" box="[1080,1091,1638,1654]" fontSize="7" pageId="26" pageNumber="189">2</subScript>
on fore wing, which is present in allied species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00DFFC2FFBCFF39EF4ACEC1" blockId="27.[125,1172,137,225]" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00DFFC2FFBCFF39EF72CE81" box="[125,304,137,161]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="80E12A4AC00DFFC2FE83FF39EFF5CE81" box="[322,439,137,161]" captionStart="Figures 75–78" captionStartId="24.[138,207,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[193,1132,141,1269]" captionTargetId="figure-47@24.[183,1140,133,1279]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figures 75–78. Female genitalia. (75) M. arenaria (BMNH Geom-20967). (76) M. cuneataria sp. nov., holotype (IZCAS Geom-00101). (77) M. inanularia sp. nov., holotype (IZCAS Geom-00102). (78) M. deveccisi (ZSM). Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5214628" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5214628/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">Figure 77</figureCitation>
). Ductus bursae and corpus bursae very short, pyriform, total length a little shorter than length of apophyses posteriores. Lamella postvaginalis broad, rectangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00DFFC2FFBCFE9AEF05CF62" blockId="27.[125,327,298,322]" box="[125,327,298,322]" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00DFFC2FFBCFE9AEEFDCF62" box="[125,191,298,322]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00DFFC2FFBCFECBEEA4CFB3" blockId="27.[125,230,379,403]" box="[125,230,379,403]" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00DFFC2FFBCFECBEEA4CFB3" box="[125,230,379,403]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="186536CFC00DFFC2FFBCFE1CEDBACC05" blockId="27.[125,1172,428,614]" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">
Weakly crenulate outer margins of both wings, absence of black ring on fore wing discal spot, curved antemedian and angled postmedian lines all distinguish this species from allied species. The female genitalia are very different from the previous two species, more similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="DFDA4D4CC00DFFC2FEC2FDBDEF9CCC05" authority="Inoue" authorityName="Inoue" box="[259,478,525,549]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Metallolophia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albescens">
<emphasis id="2AAEEADDC00DFFC2FEC2FDBDEFCCCC05" box="[259,398,525,549]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="190">M. albescens</emphasis>
Inoue
</taxonomicName>
, the markings of which are however different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
